            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-58051",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "libssh2 through 1.11.1 grows its publickey list with SSH2_REALLOC but  ..."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "libssh2 through 1.11.1 grows its publickey list with SSH2_REALLOC but does not zero-initialize new entries before parsing populates them, so a parse failure reaching the cleanup path leaves libssh2_publickey_list_free operating on an uninitialized entry. A malicious SSH server offering the publickey subsystem can use a malformed response to make cleanup free an uninitialized, attacker-influenceable attrs pointer in a connecting libssh2 client."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-58051",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-58051\nSeverity: UNKNOWN\nPackage: libssh2-1t64\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2026-58051](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-58051)\nlibssh2 through 1.11.1 grows its publickey list with SSH2_REALLOC but does not zero-initialize new entries before parsing populates them, so a parse failure reaching the cleanup path leaves libssh2_publickey_list_free operating on an uninitialized entry. A malicious SSH server offering the publickey subsystem can use a malformed response to make cleanup free an uninitialized, attacker-influenceable attrs pointer in a connecting libssh2 client.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-58051**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|UNKNOWN|libssh2-1t64||[CVE-2026-58051](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-58051)|\n\nlibssh2 through 1.11.1 grows its publickey list with SSH2_REALLOC but does not zero-initialize new entries before parsing populates them, so a parse failure reaching the cleanup path leaves libssh2_publickey_list_free operating on an uninitialized entry. A malicious SSH server offering the publickey subsystem can use a malformed response to make cleanup free an uninitialized, attacker-influenceable attrs pointer in a connecting libssh2 client."
              },
              "properties": {
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "0.0",
